@node intro Introduction

@{u}@{b}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

LANClip is a small utility that lets you share one global clipboard between
your networked Amigas (or AmigaOS clones), or Windows boxes.

Data copied to the clipboard on one computer is immediately available to paste
on other machines.

Features:

À Transparency. Cut and paste over the network as easily as between apps on
  the same computer.

À Serverless and stateless protocol. Once LANClip is set up on your LAN,
  you can turn off or on any of your Amigas without it causing LANClip
  a problem.

À Switch between local (non-shared) and global (shared) mode with a simple
  keypress.

À Pastes ALL kinds of clipboard data. You can write a Personal Paint brush
  to the clipboard on one Amiga, and paste it into iconedit on another.

  NOTE: The windows client currently only supports text.

@endnode

@node requi Requirements

@{u}@{b}Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

To use Amiga LANClip, you will need:

À 2 or more computers that are networked via TCP/IP, and have a LANClip
  client for their operating system.
À Kickstart/Workbench v2 or better
À reqtools.library v38 or better
À Applications that use the standard Amiga clipboard.device

@endnode

@node insta Installation

@{u}@{b}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

Installation is very simple. Copy the "lanclip" and "osd" executables to "C:",
and copy the preferences program to "sys:Prefs/" on every Amiga that you wish to
share clipboard data.

Next, run the preferences program, and configure LANClip to your LAN.
Instructions for this can be found @{"here" LINK prefwin}.

Now, when your TCP/IP stack is online, you can run the LANClip daemon.
Personally, I have a DOS script that is executed every time MiamiDx
starts (Events -> Start -> @Shell script ), which contains:

run <>NIL: C:LANClip

So LANClip is always available on my Amigas if a TCP/IP stack is running.

Thats it! Now LANClip is ready. Copies or cuts from one Amiga should now
be available on all the other Amigas running LANClip.

NOTE: If your network is attached to the internet, you should firewall
port 9999 from the outside world (or any other ports you use with LANClip).
Although nobody will be able to gain access to your clipboard data through that
port, they would be able to send their own clipboard data to your LAN.

@endnode

@node prefwin The Preferences Editor

@{u}@{b}The Preferences Editor@{ub}@{uu}

At the top of the preferences editor, there is a list entitled "Remote Computers".
Into this list, you have to put the IP addresses of ALL the computers that you wish
to broadcast clipboard data to.

For example, if you have 3 Amigas on your LAN, with the following IP addresses:

Amiga A = 10.0.0.1
Amiga B = 10.0.0.2
Amiga C = 10.0.0.3

You should set up Amiga A so that it has the following "Remote Computers" list:

10.0.0.2
10.0.0.3

Similarly, Amiga B would have this list:

10.0.0.1
10.0.0.3

To add an IP address, click "Add" and enter it into the box that pops up. If you
make a mistake, highlight the IP address you added and click "Modify". If you want
to remove an IP address, simply highlight it and click "Remove".

"Hotkey" contains a commodities input filter string (e.g. a keypress). When you
press the hotkey described here, LANClip will swap between local and global mode.

In local mode, your clipboard data is not broadcast to other machines, and clipboard
data received over the network is not made available to paste. Global mode activates
the clipboard sharing.

If any clipboard data is received from the network while you are in "Local" mode,
it will be stored in RAM until you switch to global mode, when it will be made
available to paste.

"Start Mode" specifies whether LANClip should start up in global or local mode.

"Save" saves the preferences permanently. "Use" sets the preferences, but once you
reboot, the last saved preferences will come back. "Cancel" quits without changing
the prefs.

If you select "Save" or "Use" while LANClip is running, it will automatically
update itself to the new preferences.

You should not need to change the "Unit", "Port" or "Timeout" boxes, but in case
you do, here is a description of their function:

* Unit

This is the unit of the clipboard.device to make public from this machine. Most
applications only use unit 0, so you should usually select this. If you have
applications that allow you to copy from or paste to other units, and you want to
have different units for local and LAN clipboards, you can change this here.

* Port

This is the port that THIS specific Amiga will listen on for connections. If you
change this, you have to update ALL the other Amigas preferences so they know
what port to talk to this Amiga on. So, if on the example LAN from above, we
were to set Amiga A to listen on port 8888, we would have to change Amiga B's
"Remote Computers" list to:

10.0.0.1:8888
10.0.0.3

Now Amiga B will try to send clipboard data to 10.0.0.1:8888, and 10.0.0.3:9999.

* Timeout (ms)

This is the number of milliseconds to wait before deciding that another Amiga on
the LAN is unavailable. When connecting over the internet, the TCP/IP stack allows
a minute or so to connect to the remote server.

This means that LANClip would wait 1 minute for every Amiga on the LAN that is
turned off, but is present in its "Remote Computers" list. Imagine if you had a LAN
with 8 Amigas, and 6 of them were off, it could take 5 minutes before the data
arrives at the other Amiga. So, to avoid this, LANClip times out much quicker,
since connections over a LAN take very little time.

If you find that LANClip won't connect to other Amigas on your LAN, you can try
increasing this value.

@endnode

@node trouble Troubleshooting

@{u}@{b}Troubleshooting@{uu}@{ub}

À LANClip won't start

Things to check:

  1) Have you run "LANClip_Prefs" and configured all the Amigas on your LAN?
  2) Is a TCP/IP stack running?
  3) Does your Amiga have kickstart 2 or newer?

À LANClip starts, but when I copy, the data doesn't arrive at my other Amiga(s)

  1) First, check that every Amiga has the IP addresses of every OTHER Amiga on
     the LAN that is running LANClip in its "Remote Computers" list, but not
     its own.
  2) Make sure that port 9999 (or other, if you changed it) is not firewalled,
     or denied to or from the Amigas you wish to share clipboards with
  3) If you changed the listening port on any of the machines, make sure all
     the other ones are set up to use that port
  4) Finally, if all else fails, try increasing the timeout. If it still doesnt
     work at 2000ms, something is wrong with your LAN settings.


@endnode

